from a southern Chinese tomb, and a fragment of Byzantine silk wrapping the bones of a French saint to a Bactrian ewer depicting episodes from the Trojan War, these objects show us something of the cultural diversity and interaction along these trading routes of Afro-Eurasia. Exploring the labor, tools, materials, and rituals behind these various objects, Whitfield infuses her narrative with delightful details as the objects journey through time, space, and meaning. Silk, Slaves, and Stupas is a lively, visual, and tangible way to understand the Silk Road and the cultural, economic, and technical changes of the late antique and medieval worlds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMaterial culturezSilk Road. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh  aafro eurasia.  aamluk dara stupa.  aancient network.  aasian history.  abartrian ewer.  ablue qur an.  abyzantine hunter silk.  achinese almanac.  aconnecting the east and the west.  acultural diversity.  acultural studies.  aeuropean history.  aglass bowl.  aglobal history.  akhotanese plaque.  akushan coins.  alabor.  alife along the silk road.  amaterial culture.  amaterials.  amedieval.  arituals.  asilk road.  aslavery.  asteppe earrings.  atools.  atrade routes.  aunknown slave.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052028177640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095766440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520957664423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520957664/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles